Colorado State University — Geospatial AI Crop Yield Forecasting
Background
Accurate and timely crop yield forecasting is critical for food security, commodity markets,
agricultural policy, and decision making. Traditional yield estimation methods often rely on surveybased approaches that can be slow, costly, and limited in spatial resolution. Recent advances in
geospatial AI, satellite remote sensing, and machine learning now offer the opportunity to produce
faster, more granular, and more accurate yield forecasts directly from Earth observation data.
Problem Statement
Using Prithvi, NASA's open-source geospatial AI foundation model, combined with NASA satellite
imagery, NAIP (National Agriculture Imagery Program) aerial imagery, and historical corn yield data
from USDA NASS (National Agricultural Statistics Service), participants are challenged to build a
geospatial machine learning pipeline that:
1. Models corn for grain yield estimates at four key points during the growing season:
o August 1 — Early grain fill
o September 1 — Late grain fill / dough stage
o October 1 — Maturity / early harvest
o Final (End of Season) — Post-harvest reconciliation
2. Generates a cone of uncertainty around each yield estimate, derived from:
o Historical seasons with analogous weather patterns
o Similar weather and geospatial signals at the same point in the season
o Actual USDA NASS reported outcomes from those analog years
3. Produces growing season yield estimates for the following five states: Iowa, Colorado,
Wisconsin, Missouri and Nebraska.
